To produce plots in R, we will use a package in the Tidyverse called ggplot(). To create any type of plot in ggplot, you should follow this formula:

For plots with only an x-axis: data %>% ggplot(aes(x=VARIABLE)) + [PLOT_TYPE]

For plots with an x and y-axis: data %>% ggplot(aes(x=[VARIABLE], y=[VARIABLE])) + [PLOT_TYPE]

ggplot produces plots according to a grammar of graphics. Just like how the Tidyverse allows us to string together functions with the pipe, ggplot allows us to string together plot attributes with a plus (+) sign. Using the plus sign, we can do things like: - add titles data %>% ggplot(aes(x=[VARIABLE], y=[VARIABLE])) + [PLOT_TYPE] + labs(title = [TITLE])

  • add axis labels data %>% ggplot(aes(x=[VARIABLE], y=[VARIABLE])) + [PLOT_TYPE] + labs(x = [XAXIS], y = [YAXIS])

  • set x and y axis limits data %>% ggplot(aes(x=[VARIABLE], y=[VARIABLE])) + [PLOT_TYPE] + xlim(0,1000) + ylim(0,200)

  • display tick labels vertically rather than horizontally data %>% ggplot(aes(x=[VARIABLE], y=[VARIABLE])) + [PLOT_TYPE] + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))

We can add additional categorical variables to column charts, using the fill aesthetic. When we set the fill aesthetic to another categorical variable, each column in the chart will be broken into different color segments, representing a value within the categorical variable. The size of the colored segement will depend on the number of times that value appears alongside the column value in the dataset. In this way, fill produces stacked bar charts that demonstrate the proportion of values in one variable that are present alongside values in a second variable.
